               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-322-person2326">
                  JAMES 
                  ROBINSON
               <interp inst="t18310908-322-person2326" type="surname" value="ROBINSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-322-person2326" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-322-person2326" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a gate-keeper of St. James'-park. On the 31st of August I stopped two boys from going into the Park, because they had pinafores on; the prisoner came and asked why I turned them out - she went away with them; I saw her talking to them a few yards from the gate, and then lost sight of her.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-322-person2327">
                  WILLIAM 
                  CRICK
               <interp inst="t18310908-322-person2327" type="surname" value="CRICK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-322-person2327" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-322-person2327" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Policeman. On the 31st of August I found two poor children close to Shoreditch church, crying - they were stripped; I made inquiry, and another constable found their parents out two days afterwards; I took one of them to Shoreditch poor-house.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-322-person2328">
                  PATRICK 
                  MURPHY
               <interp inst="t18310908-322-person2328" type="surname" value="MURPHY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-322-person2328" type="given" value="PATRICK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-322-person2328" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a labourer. On the 31st of August I saw one child crying in Shoreditch, it was a boy; he had nothing on but a pinafore, and a small pair of trousers.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-322-person2329">
                  CAROLINE 
                  MARTHA NEWTON
               <interp inst="t18310908-322-person2329" type="surname" value="MARTHA NEWTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-322-person2329" type="given" value="CAROLINE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-322-person2329" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am eleven years old. I went to the Park with my two little brothers; the keeper would not let us in, because we had pinafores on, and I was not old enough to mind them; the prisoner came up, and told us to keep inside the Park; I said the keeper would not let us; she spoke to him; she then came and told me to go round to the Horse-guards' gate; she was then within a few yards of Storey's-gate; she gave me a penny, and said, "Go and get a penny worth of apples" - I had some playthings and an apple in my lap; she said, "That apple is not large enough for you, go and fetch a pennyworth;" I went, and when I came back she was gone, and my two brothers too - I was not gone long; I said, "William and Johnny don't go away"- she said, "No, I'll take care of that;" one of them is six and the other four years old.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-322-person2330">
                  JOSEPH 
                  HAWKRIGG
               <interp inst="t18310908-322-person2330" type="surname" value="HAWKRIGG"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-322-person2330" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-322-person2330" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I belong to Aldersgate-street parish. The prisoner was given into my custody at Guildhall on another charge; I heard of these children being stolen, and had her detained; Newton took his children to the prison - they are too ill to be brought here, and have been so ever since.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-322-person2331">
                  ROBERT 
                  NEWTON
               <interp inst="t18310908-322-person2331" type="surname" value="NEWTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-322-person2331" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-322-person2331" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in Tothill-street, Westminster. From Wednesday to Friday I was in the greatest distress about my children, and out day and night; I found one in the workhouse in Shoe-lane, and the other in Shoreditch workhouse - the youngest had a pinafore over him, with his little trousers; the other had scarcely any thing on - I took my daughter, Caroline, to the prison; all the female prisoners were turned into the yard; she pointed the prisoner out among twenty, immediately; I have not found their clothes.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I did not strip the children, or take any thing from them - I was at Red-Lion-square in the evening from half-past four o'clock.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18310908-322-verdict1658" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18310908-322-verdict1658" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 32. - <rs id="t18310908-322-punish1659" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18310908-322-punish1659" type="punishmentCategory" value="transport"></interp>
                     <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310908-322-defend2323 t18310908-322-punish1659"></join>
               Transported for Life
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>See page 831. - There was also another indictment against her.</p>
